SIMPLE: weaken
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Weaken
<hw>Weak"en</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Weakened</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Weakening</conjf>.]</vmorph>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To make weak; to lessen the strength of; to deprive
of strength; to debilitate; to enfeeble; to enervate; <as>as, to
<ex>weaken</ex> the body or the mind; to <ex>weaken</ex> the hands of a
magistrate; to <ex>weaken</ex> the force of an objection or an
argument</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their hands shall be <qex>weakened</qex> from the work, that it be
not done.</q> <rj><qau>Neh. vi. 9.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To reduce in quality, strength, or spirit; <as>as,
to <ex>weaken</ex> tea; to <ex>weaken</ex> any solution or
decoction</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Weaken</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Weaken
<hw>Weak"en</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To become weak or weaker; to
lose strength, spirit, or determination; to become less positive or
resolute; <as>as, the patient <ex>weakened</ex>; the witness
<ex>weakened</ex> on cross-examination</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧His notion
<xex>weakens</xex>, his discernings are lethargied.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Weakener</ent>⟦br⟧
